{[show NESW]
[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead] Lead the \C4, fourth-best from your longest suit — the standard start against 3NT.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end] You are in 3NT needing nine tricks. The spade suit — your A-Q-8-4 opposite dummy's J-T — is missing the king with THREE guards: no number of ordinary finesses picks up K-7-5-3, because the fourth round always belongs to the king. Unless… the king's guards do not survive to the fourth round. Run your diamonds first and watch what East throws: every spade he releases shortens the wall around his king.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead] The club lead comes to your queen. Diamonds now — all four rounds, ending in dummy — and there it is: East lets a SPADE go. His king now has two guards, not three. Ride dummy's TEN — it holds. The JACK — covered? no, it holds too. And now the count is complete: his king is bare, so the ACE goes up and the king falls under it, the queen and eight your dividends. FOUR spade tricks against a four-card king; nine tricks home.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play] A suit that could NOT be picked up was picked up anyway, because the squeeze softened it first: the diamond run cost East a guard, the finesses ate two more, and the show-up finished it. Notice the order — pressure first, finesses second, the drop last. Count the guards, not just the honors; when the guards run out, the honor is yours for the asking.}
