{[show NESW]
[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead] Lead the \HK, top of your \HK-Q sequence in your longest suit — the standard attack against 3NT.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end] You are in 3NT needing nine tricks. Five clubs and the two red winners come to seven-plus, and spades must do the rest — but look closely at \SA-K-J-4 opposite 9-2: the queen is missing, and if WEST holds her she sits OVER your jack. Lead low to the jack and she simply takes it: for you there is NO spade finesse. So do not invent one. Run the clubs first and count the cards that leave West's hand — a queen with fewer companions is a queen in trouble.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead] Duck the heart king — your nine falls — and win the second heart with the ace. Now the clubs, all five of them, ending in dummy: on the run East lets a spade go, and WEST does too. There is the whole story: her queen began with two guards and now keeps one. Cash the \SK — her six appears — and the \SA: the QUEEN falls under it, exactly as the count promised. Your \SJ, the card no finesse could ever have promoted, is the ninth trick. The defense keeps the diamond ace and two hearts; nine tricks are yours.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play] The jack was trapped from the deal — West's queen sat over it, and no lead from any hand could change that. What the finesse could not do, the count did: five rounds of clubs cost the queen her guards, and the ace executed her in public. An offside queen cannot be finessed — but she can be counted to death. When the finesse does not exist, the squeeze is not a flourish; it is the only line.}
