{[show NESW]
[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead] Lead the \CA, top of your ace-king — cash it and study dummy before committing to more against the spade game.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end] Partner transferred and offered 3NT; your ace-third of spades chose the five-three fit, and 4\S needs ten tricks. The suit to read is hearts: your \HA-K-T-9-5 opposite dummy's bare 8. If West holds Q-J-x they sit OVER your ten, and every finesse in the suit is stillborn. But you hold a second threat — the \CJ, alive once the defenders' top clubs are spent — and dummy's diamonds will apply the pressure. West cannot guard your jack of clubs AND keep three hearts. Make him choose.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead] West cashes the club ace and puts partner in with the queen; East returns a trump to your ace. Unblock the \DK-Q-J, cross in trumps — West takes his trump king along the way — and play the third diamond: West must find a discard, and a HEART leaves his hand, for his clubs must keep guarding your jack. From Q-J-6 to Q-J tight. Now the harvest: the \HK drops his jack, the \HA his queen, and your ten and nine stand over East's small cards. Ten tricks — three hearts more than the finesse could ever have won you.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play] Count West's dilemma: he began with the club ace-king-ten over your jack and queen-jack-six over your ten of hearts — two guards, one hand. The third diamond was the question, and any answer cost a trick. He kept the clubs, so the hearts fell: king takes jack, ace takes queen, and the ten-nine — losers at trick one — took tricks of their own. When both your threats live, the defender's discard is not information; it is surrender.}
