{[show NESW]
[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead] Lead the \S3, fourth-best from your longest suit. Nothing is truly safe against 6NT, and with tens in every other suit an attacking lead from the king is as good a try as any.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end] Puppet found no major, Gerber found three aces, and 6NT needs twelve tricks: count eleven on top once the clubs behave. The spade suit is the battleground — \SA-Q-8 opposite J-9-2 — and the opening lead has already drawn the map: a low spade at trick one, into a slam, is a lead away from the KING. He sits over your queen, so the finesse you were born to take is already dead. Take what the lead gifts you, then run your winners and count his hand instead.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead] The three rides around to your EIGHT — trick one from nowhere, and the king marked behind your queen. Now grind: king of diamonds, both club honors in dummy, hearts to the king and jack, the diamond ace. Under the minors West lets one spade go, then another — from K-x-x to the king alone; you concede the diamond East's queen was always winning, win the heart return, and lead dummy's \S9 — not to finesse, there is no finesse — up with the ACE, and the king falls bare beneath it. At trick thirteen the \SQ, frozen under that king since the deal was dealt, takes the last trick. Twelve.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play] The lead told you where the king was; the count told you when he stood alone. Between those two facts the "hopeless" spade position paid three tricks — the gifted eight, the executing ace, the promoted queen — and the finesse was never taken because it never existed. That is the show-up squeeze at full depth: the run strips the guards, the ace collects the confession, and the trapped queen has the last word.}
